@using System.Web.Optimization
@using QOAM.Core
@using QOAM.Website.Helpers
@using QOAM.Website.Models
@{
    ViewBag.Title = "Journal Score Card";
}

@helper JournalScoreCardImage(string name, string description)
{
    <a class="jscimage" rel="jscimage" href="~/Images/ScoreCards/journalscorecard-@(name).png" title="@description">
        <img src="~/Images/ScoreCards/journalscorecard-@(name)-small.png" alt="@description" />
    </a>
}

<div class="container main">
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-3">
            @{ Html.RenderPartial("_SidebarMenu", "JournalScoreCard"); }
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-9">
            <h2>@ViewBag.Title</h2>

            <ul class="list-unstyled">
                <li><a href="#basejournalscorecard">Base Journal Score Card</a></li>
                <li><a href="#valuationjournalscorecard">Valuation Journal Score Card</a></li>
                <li><a href="#how-used">How are JSCs used in QOAM?</a></li>
                <li><a href="#swot">The SWOT matrix</a></li>
                <li><a href="#life-cycle">The life cycle of  Journal Score Cards</a></li>
            </ul>

            <h3 id="basejournalscorecard">Base Journal Score Card</h3>
            <p>The Base Score Card is a questionnaire on the transparancy of the journal’s website with respect to the following aspects:  Editorial information, Peer review, Governance and Process. Every aspect has some bullets and each bullet can be rated from 1 to 5. The average of these ratings is called the subscore for this aspect. The lowest subscore of these four aspects is called the <strong>Base Score</strong> of the journal.</p>

            <p>1. @QuestionCategory.EditorialInformation.GetName()</p>
            <ul>
                <li>@QuestionKey.WebsiteContainsAimsScopeAndReadership.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.WebsiteContainsNameAndAffiliationsOfMembersEditorialBoard.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.ReviewsCommentsArePublished.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.WebsiteContainsRoleOfMembersEditorialBoard.ToDescription()</li>
            </ul>

            <p>2. @QuestionCategory.PeerReview.GetName()</p>
            <ul>
                <li>@QuestionKey.WebsiteContainsSubmissionsReviewDetails.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.WebsiteContainsCriteriaUsedByReviewers.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.AuthorsAllowedToIndicateDesiredReviewers.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.WebsiteAllowsRatingsAndCommentariesOfPapers.ToDescription()</li>
            </ul>

            <p>3. @QuestionCategory.Governance.GetName()</p>
            <ul>
                <li>@QuestionKey.HasClearGuidelinesConcerningSharing.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.CopiesAreMadeInThirdPartyRepositories.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.TakesCareOfInclusionInRelevantIndexingServices.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.HighlightsIssuesOfPublicationEthics.ToDescription()</li>
            </ul>

            <p>4. @QuestionCategory.Process.GetName()</p>
            <ul>
                <li>@QuestionKey.ProvidesTrackAndTraceService.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.PublishedPapersIncludeInformationOnDatesOfSubmissionAndAcceptance.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.ProvidesArticlesWithDigitalObjectIdentifier.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.DisclosesNumberOfSubmissionsPublicationsAndRejectionRates.ToDescription()</li>
            </ul>

            <p>Additional question</p>

            <p>
                <em>
                    <label>What does the website of the journal tell about the publication fee?</label>
                </em>

                <div>
                    <input type="radio" id="outdatedPublication-article">
                    <em>
                        <label for="outdatedPublication-article">Price per article</label>
                    </em>
                    <input type="radio" id="outdatedPublication-page">
                    <em>
                        <label for="outdatedPublication-page">Price per page</label>
                    </em>
                    <input type="radio" id="outdatedPublication-nofee">
                    <em>
                        <label for="outdatedPublication-nofee">No Fee</label>
                    </em>
                    <input type="radio" id="outdatedPublication-absent">
                    <em>
                        <label for="outdatedPublication-absent">Absent or diffuse</label>
                    </em>
                </div>
            </p>

            <p>
                Pop up box in case the first or second checkbox is ticked:
            </p>

            <p>
                <select class="priceBox">
                    <option value="0">US Dollar</option>
                    <option value="1">Euro</option>
                    <option value="2">UK Pound</option>
                </select>

                <input type="text" class="form-control inline" placeholder="Price per article">
            </p>

            <p>
                <input type="text" class="form-control" placeholder="Free text box for supplementary comments." />
            </p>

            <h3 id="valuationjournalscorecard">Valuation Journal Score Card</h3>
            <p>The Valuation Score Card is a reality check, preferably based on experience as an author, editor or peer reviewer of the journal.  It has three bullets that can be rated from 1 to 5 and the average of these ratings is called the <strong>Valuation Score</strong> of the journal. </p>

            <p>@QuestionCategory.Valuation.GetName()</p>
            <ul>
                <li>I have published an article in this journal less than a year ago</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.PeerReviewProcessTransparent.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.RecommendScholarsToSubmit.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>@QuestionKey.GoodValueForMoney.ToDescription()</li>
                <li>Publication of my article in this journal did cost</li>
            </ul>

            <p>Additional questions</p>
            <p>
                <input type="checkbox" /> I have published an article in this journal less than a year ago
            </p>

            <p>
                Pop up box in case the first or second checkbox is ticked:
            </p>

            <p>
                Publication of my article in this journal did cost
                
                <select class="priceBox">
                    <option value="0">US Dollar</option>
                    <option value="1">Euro</option>
                    <option value="2">UK Pound</option>
                </select>

                <input type="text" class="form-control inline" placeholder="Price per article">
            </p>

            <p>
                <input type="checkbox" /> I am an editor of this journal
            </p>

            <p>
                <input type="text" class="form-control" placeholder="Free text box for supplementary comments." />
            </p>

            <h3 id="how-used">How are JSCs used in QOAM?</h3>
            <p>Journals in QOAM may have a Base Score, a Valuation Score or both. Journals can be sorted on both scores. It is possible to confine a search to journals with a Valuation Score.</p>

            <p>
                Because the Base Score is the lowest of the four web based subscores, a journal with a high Base Score, has a web site that addresses all the journal aspects adequately. On the other hand, a journal with a low Base Score has at least one weak aspect, but may still be strong in other respects. In order to climb on the list a journal must address its weakest aspect.
            </p>

            <p>
                QOAM has the option to filter journals per title key word, ISSN, publisher, discipline and language. Filtering per discipline enables to take the varied recognition of different aspects over disciplines into account. E.g. if speed of publication is less important in a specific discipline all journals in this discipline will produce a lower subscore for the aspect ‘process’, which might be their Base Score. In a general search this would result in a place at the bottom of the ranking. Within their own discipline the other aspects become more profiling.
            </p>

            <p>
                On top of that, every author can decide for herself which aspects she deems most relevant. Per journal all aspect subscores are produced.
            </p>

            <h3 id="swot">The SWOT matrix</h3>
            <img src="~/Images/swot.png" />

            <h3 id="life-cycle">The life cycle of  Journal Score Cards</h3>
            <p>
                To avoid framing only members of the academic community can publish Journal Score Cards. Therefore, their institute must be connected to QOAM so that they can log in to the scoring section of QOAM with their institutional id. Usually, library staff publish Base JSCs; authors, editors and peer reviewers publish Valuation JSCs. Per person only one JSC may be published for a specific journal. In case several people publish a JSC for the same journal the averaged subscores will be attributed to the journal.
            </p>

            <p>
                In order to reflect new developments of or new experiences with the journal, everybody may edit their JSC at any moment. Updated Journal Score Cards will be dealt with as newly published ones.
            </p>

            <p>
                The Base Score and the Valuation Score are averaged from the scores of the preceding year.  A month before a JSC becomes ineffective its author will be notified of this and will be invited to update their JSC (provided they are still a member of the academic community.) In case of no response the Journal Score Card will be open-archived in QOAM.
            </p>

            <p>
                The Journal Score Card’s format will be evaluated periodically and possibly adapted to new insights. However, changes will not be abrupt and draft versions will be circulated for comment prior to installation. As JSCs are only effective for a year the migration period in which ‘old’ and ‘new’ subscores sit together lasts a year at most. Effectively the migration period could be shorter because everybody may edit their JSC at any time. Thus, the JSC may evolve organically.
            </p>

        </div>
    </div>
</div>

@section stylesheets
{
    @Styles.Render("~/styles/fancybox")
}

@section scripts
{
    @Scripts.Render("~/scripts/fancybox")

    <script type="text/javascript">
        $(function () {
            var homeController = new HomeController();
            homeController.journalScoreCard();
        });
    </script>
}
